In a group setting, bards shine, no one here disputes this-<br>
As this is about raids that supposedly have an exp group makeup per group, the same would hold true, no?<br>
If it's about not being needed for resists, that is an issue not based just on bards, and supposedly SOE is addressing caps on that.<br>
If you are looking for a 100% role that is irreplaceable on a raid, no class has it, name one-You can run any raid out there with zero clerics(druids) zero warriors(pally/sk), the list goes on-Doesnt make it easy, just possible.<br>
Due to the simple fact we were perceived as indispensable in AE raids when a bard addition could scoff at AE, isn't true anymore. Welcome to the rest of the EQ world, where no class can any longer stick a finger in the glass of water and leave a hole, as a bard used to be able to. If you have skills as a bard, you bring alot to a raid, any raid, and any group that has you in it knows what utility you bring, if they have a brain in their head. I shouldn't have to tell an end game person what thier utility is, unless the biggest one they bring is pressing ele chorus or Chorus of Marr and going AFK.<br>
Yeah maybe a 4th bard in a traditional raid setting has less use than one bard which isn't enough traditionally, but be the fourth shaman, or sk,or ranger, or monk, or alot of other classes. Your primary purpose as a bard in a raid may not be there like it has been to the same extent, but your utility is, and while you now don't show as much of the big things as being useful to the same degree(like ae resists, mana), I would think the little things, the jackofalltradescosmicglue things a bard brings to a group will still shine. I know I am busy on a raid, even with 4 bards on it. Why aren't you? <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.wildcarddesigns.com/images/edsigb.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
